        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-11-30T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-11-30T20:00:00-05:00" n="799" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d799">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.24/11–2945: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-11-30T20:00:00-05:00">November 30, 1945—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2431. Urtel 4009, November 29.<note n="22" xml:id="d799fn22">Not printed; it
                        requested information on “status of any negotiations of Soviet Govt for
                        Export-Import Bank credit.” (861.51/11–2945)</note> From Clayton. Since
                    preliminary discussions between Mr. Crowley and General Rudenko in which General
                    Rudenko requested a line of credit of $1 billion for purchase of equipment in
                    U.S. and which did not result in any commitment on part of this Government, no
                    further discussions have taken place.</p>
                <p>Dept has been pursuing policy of not encouraging active discussions and at
                    present matter is dormant. [Clayton.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Byrnes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
